# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: z-wave-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] The phrase **smart home** refers to home automation devices that have internet access.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] Home automation, a broader category, includes *any* device that can be monitored or controlled via wireless radio signals, not just those having internet access.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] When connected with the Internet, home sensors and activation devices are an important constituent of the Internet of Things ("IoT").
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] A home automation system typically connects controlled devices to a central smart home hub (sometimes called a "gateway").
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] The user interface for control of the system uses either wall-mounted terminals, tablet or desktop computers, a mobile phone application, or a Web interface that may also be accessible off-site through the Internet.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] Early home automation began with labor-saving machines.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] Self-contained electric or gas powered home appliances became viable in the 1900s with the introduction of electric power distribution and led to the introduction of washing machines (1904), water heaters (1889), refrigerators (1913), sewing machines, dishwashers, and clothes dryers.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] In 1975, the first general purpose home automation network technology, X10, was developed.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] It is a communication protocol for electronic devices.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] It primarily uses electric power transmission wiring for signalling and control, where the signals involve brief radio frequency bursts of digital data, and remains the most widely available.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] By 2012, in the United States, according to ABI Research, 1.5 million home automation systems were installed.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] Per research firm Statista more than 45 million smart home devices will be installed in U.S. homes by the end of the year 2018.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] From 2018 to 2023, the number of U.S. homes equipped with smart devices grew at 10.2% per year to reach 63.43 million by 2023.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] The word "*domotics*" is a contraction of the Latin word for a home (*domus*) and the word *robotics*.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] The word "smart" in "smart home" refers to the system being aware of the state of its devices, which is done through the information and communication technologies (ICT) protocol and the Internet of Things (IoT).
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] In 2011, Microsoft Research found that home automation could involve a high cost of ownership, inflexibility of interconnected devices, and poor manageability.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] When designing and creating a home automation system, engineers take into account several factors including scalability, how well the devices can be monitored and controlled, ease of installation and use for the consumer, affordability, speed, security, and ability to diagnose issues.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] Findings from iControl showed that consumers prioritize ease-of-use over technical innovation, and although consumers recognize that new connected devices have an unparalleled cool factor, they are not quite ready to use them in their own homes yet.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] Historically, systems have been sold as complete systems where the consumer relies on one vendor for the entire system including the hardware, the communications protocol, the central hub, and the user interface.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] However, there are now open hardware and open source software systems which can be used instead of or with proprietary hardware.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] Many of these systems interface with consumer electronics such as the Arduino or Raspberry Pi, which are easily accessible online and in most electronics stores.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] In addition, home automation devices are increasingly interfaced with mobile phones through Bluetooth, allowing for increased affordability and customizability for the user.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] Customers may hesitate to bet their IoT future on proprietary software or hardware devices that use proprietary protocols that may fade or become difficult to customize and interconnect.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] The nature of home automation devices can also be a problem for security, data security and data privacy, since patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-price devices.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] One set of researchers say that the failure of vendors to support older devices with patches and updates leaves more than 87% of active devices vulnerable.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] Concerns have been raised by tenants renting from landlords who decide to upgrade units with smart home technology.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] These concerns include weak wireless connections that render the door or appliance unusable or impractical; the security of door passcodes kept by the landlord; and the potential invasion of privacy that comes with connecting smart home technologies to home networks.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] Researchers have also conducted user studies to determine what the barriers are for consumers when integrating home automation devices or systems into their daily lifestyle.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] One of the main takeaways was regarding ease of use, as consumers tend to steer towards "plug and play" solutions over more complicated setups.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] One study found that there were large gaps in the mental-models generated by users regarding how the devices actually work.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] Specifically, the findings showed that there was a lot of misunderstanding related to where the data collected by smart devices was stored and how it was used.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] For example, in a smart light setup, one participant thought that her iPad communicated directly with the light, telling it to either turn-off or on.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] In reality, the iPad sends a signal to the cloud system that the company uses (in this case, the Hue Bridge) which then signals directly to the device.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] Overall, this field is still evolving and the nature of each device is constantly changing.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] While technologists work to create more secure, streamlined, and standardized security protocols, consumers also need to learn more about how these devices work and what the implications of putting them in their homes can be.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] The growth of this field is currently limited not only by technology but also by a user's ability to trust a device and integrate it successfully into his/her daily life.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] Utilizing home automation could lead to more efficient and intelligent energy-saving techniques.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] To do this, researchers propose using data from sensors regarding consumer activity within the home to anticipate consumer needs and balance that with energy consumption.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] Furthermore, home automation has a large potential regarding family safety and security.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] According to a 2015 survey done by iControl, the primary drivers of the demand for smart and connected devices are first "personal and family security", and second "excitement about energy savings".
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] Home automation includes a variety of smart security systems and surveillance setups.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] This allows consumers to monitor their homes while away, and to give trusted family members access to that information in case anything bad happens.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] While there are many competing vendors, there are increasing efforts towards open source systems.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] However, there are issues with the current state of home automation including a lack of standardized security measures and deprecation of older devices without backwards compatibility.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] Home automation has high potential for sharing data between family members or trusted individuals for personal security purposes and could lead to energy saving measures with a positive environmental impact in the future.
[src:z-wave-deep/home-automation] The home automation market was worth US$64 billion in 2022 and is projected to grow to over $163 billion in 2028.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] The **ISM radio bands** are portions of the radio spectrum reserved internationally for *industrial, scientific and medical* (ISM) purposes, excluding applications in telecommunications.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Examples of applications for the use of radio frequency (RF) energy in these bands include RF heating, microwave ovens, and medical diathermy machines.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] The powerful emissions of these devices can create electromagnetic interference and disrupt radio communication using the same frequency, so these devices are limited to certain bands of frequencies.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] In general, communications equipment operating in ISM bands must tolerate any interference generated by ISM applications, and users have no regulatory protection from ISM device operation in these bands.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Cordless phones, Bluetooth devices, near-field communication (NFC) devices, garage door openers, baby monitors, and wireless computer networks (Wi-Fi) may all use the ISM frequencies, although these low-power transmitters are not considered to be ISM devices.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] The ISM bands are defined by the ITU Radio Regulations (article 5) in footnotes 5.138, 5.150, and 5.280 of the Radio Regulations.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Individual countries' use of the bands designated in these sections may differ due to variations in national radio regulations.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Because communication devices using the ISM bands must tolerate any interference from ISM equipment, unlicensed operations are typically permitted to use these bands, since unlicensed operation typically needs to be tolerant of interference from other devices anyway.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] The ISM bands share allocations with unlicensed and licensed operations; however, due to the high likelihood of harmful interference, licensed use of the bands is typically low.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] In the United States, uses of the ISM bands are governed by Part 18 of the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) rules, while Part 15 contains the rules for unlicensed communication devices, even those that share ISM frequencies.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] In Europe, the ETSI develops standards for the use of short-range devices, some of which operate in ISM bands.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] The use of the ISM bands is regulated by the national spectrum regulation authorities that are members of the CEPT.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] The allocation of radio frequencies is provided according to *Article 5* of the ITU Radio Regulations (edition 2012).
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] In order to improve harmonisation in spectrum utilisation, the majority of service allocations stipulated in this document were incorporated in national tables of frequency allocations and utilisations which are within the responsibilities of the appropriate national administrations.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] The allocation might be primary, secondary, exclusive, or shared.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Exclusive or shared utilization is within the responsibility of administrations.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] ITU RR, (Footnote 5.280) = In Germany, Austria, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, North Macedonia, Liechtenstein, Montenegro, Portugal, Serbia, Slovenia and Switzerland, the band 433.05–434.79 MHz (center frequency 433.92 MHz) is designated for *ISM applications*.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Radio communication services of these countries operating within this band must accept harmful interference which may be caused by these applications.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] The ISM bands were first established at the International Telecommunications Conference of the ITU in Atlantic City, 1947.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] The American delegation specifically proposed several bands, including the now commonplace 2.4 GHz band, to accommodate the then nascent process of microwave heating; however, FCC annual reports of that time suggest that much preparation was done ahead of these presentations.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Radio frequencies in the ISM bands have been used for communication purposes, although such devices may experience interference from non-communication sources.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] In the U.S., the FCC first made unlicensed spread spectrum available in the ISM bands in rules adopted on May 9, 1985.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] The FCC action was proposed by Michael Marcus of the FCC staff in 1980 and the subsequent regulatory action took five more years.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] It was part of a broader proposal to allow civil use of spread spectrum technology and was opposed at the time by mainstream equipment manufacturers and many radio system operators.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Many other countries later developed similar regulations, enabling use of this technology.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] The original ISM specifications envisioned that the bands would be used primarily for noncommunication purposes, such as heating.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] The bands are still widely used for these purposes.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] For many people, the most commonly encountered ISM device is the home microwave oven operating at 2.45 GHz which uses microwaves to cook food.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Industrial heating is another big application area; such as induction heating, microwave heat treating, plastic softening, and plastic welding processes.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] In medical settings, shortwave and microwave diathermy machines use radio waves in the ISM bands to apply deep heating to the body for relaxation and healing.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] More recently hyperthermia therapy uses microwaves to heat tissue to kill cancer cells.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] These are sometimes called "non ISM" uses since they do not fall under the originally envisioned "industrial", "scientific", and "medical" application areas.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] One of the largest applications has been wireless networking (Wi-Fi).
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] The IEEE 802.11ah wireless networking protocols, the standards on which almost all wireless systems are based, use the ISM bands.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Virtually all laptops, tablet computers, computer printers and cellphones now have 802.11 wireless modems using the 2.4 and 5.7 GHz ISM bands.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Bluetooth is another networking technology using the 2.4 GHz band, which can be problematic given the probability of interference.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Near-field communication (NFC) devices such as proximity cards and contactless smart cards use the lower-frequency 13 and 27 MHz ISM bands.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Multiple international LoRa standards use ISM bands for low-power, long-range, low-rate data transmission.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Some electrodeless lamp designs are ISM devices, which use RF emissions to excite fluorescent tubes.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Sulfur lamps are commercially available plasma lamps, which use 2.45 GHz magnetrons to heat sulfur into a brightly glowing plasma.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Long-distance wireless power systems have been proposed and experimented with which would use high-power transmitters and rectennas, in lieu of overhead transmission lines and underground cables, to send power to remote locations.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] NASA has studied using microwave power transmission on 2.45 GHz to send energy collected by solar power satellites back to the ground.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Also in space applications, a helicon double-layer ion thruster is a prototype spacecraft propulsion engine which uses a 13.56 MHz transmission to break down and heat gas into plasma.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] In recent years ISM bands have also been shared with (non-ISM) license-free error-tolerant communications applications such as wireless sensor networks in the 915 MHz and 2.450 GHz bands, as well as wireless LANs and cordless phones in the 915 MHz, 2.450 GHz, and 5.800 GHz bands.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Because unlicensed devices are required to be tolerant of ISM emissions in these bands, unlicensed low-power users are generally able to operate in these bands without causing problems for ISM users.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] ISM equipment does not necessarily include a radio receiver in the ISM band (e.g. a microwave oven does not have a receiver).
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] In the United States, according to 47 CFR Part 15.5, low power communication devices must accept interference from licensed users of that frequency band, and the Part 15 device must not cause interference to licensed users.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Note that the 915 MHz band should not be used in countries outside Region 2, except those that specifically allow it, such as Australia (915 MHz to 928 MHz) and Israel, especially those that use the GSM-900 band for cellphones.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] The ISM bands are also widely used for radio-frequency identification (RFID) applications with the most commonly used band being the 13.56 MHz band used by systems compliant with ISO/IEC 14443 including those used by biometric passports and contactless smart cards.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] In Europe, the use of the ISM band is covered by Short Range Device regulations issued by European Commission, based on technical recommendations by CEPT and standards by ETSI.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] In most of Europe, LPD433 band is allowed for license-free voice communication in addition to PMR446.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Wireless LANs and cordless phones can also use bands other than those shared with ISM, but such uses require approval on a country by country basis.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] DECT phones use allocated spectrum outside the ISM bands that differs in Europe and North America.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Ultra-wideband LANs require more spectrum than the ISM bands can provide, so the relevant standards such as IEEE 802.15.4a are designed to make use of spectrum outside the ISM bands.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Despite the fact that these additional bands are outside the official ITU-R ISM bands, because they are used for the same types of low power personal communications, they are sometimes incorrectly referred to as ISM bands as well.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Several brands of radio control equipment use the 2.4 GHz band range for low power remote control of toys, from gas powered cars to miniature aircraft.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Worldwide Digital Cordless Telecommunications or WDCT is a technology that uses the 2.4 GHz radio spectrum.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Google's Project Loon used ISM bands (specifically 2.4 and 5.8 GHz bands) for balloon-to-balloon and balloon-to-ground communications.
[src:z-wave-deep/ism-radio-band] Pursuant to 47 CFR Part 97 some ISM bands are used by licensed amateur radio operators for communication – including amateur television.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] A **mesh network** is a network topology in which the infrastructure nodes (i.e., bridges, switches, and other infrastructure devices) connect directly, dynamically and non-hierarchically to as many other nodes as possible and cooperate with one another to efficiently route data to and from hosts.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] This lack of dependency on one node allows for every node to participate in the relay of information.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] Mesh networks dynamically self-organize and self-configure, which can reduce installation overhead.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] The ability to self-configure enables dynamic distribution of workloads, particularly in the event that a few nodes should fail.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] This, in turn, contributes to fault-tolerance and reduced maintenance costs.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] Mesh topology may be contrasted with conventional star/tree network topologies in which the bridges/switches are directly linked to only a small subset of other bridges/switches, and the links between these infrastructure neighbours are hierarchical.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] While star-and-tree topologies are very well established, highly standardized and vendor-neutral, vendors of mesh network devices have not yet all agreed on common standards, and interoperability between devices from different vendors is not yet assured.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] Mesh networks can relay messages using either a *flooding* or a *routing* technique, which makes them different from non-mesh networks.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] A routed message is propagated along a path by *hopping* from node to node until it reaches its destination.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] To ensure that all its paths are available, the network must allow for continuous connections and must reconfigure itself around broken paths, using *self-healing* algorithms such as Shortest Path Bridging and TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links).
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] Self-healing allows a routing-based network to operate when a node breaks down or when a connection becomes unreliable.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] The network is typically quite reliable, as there is often more than one path between a source and a destination in the network.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] Although mostly used in wireless situations, this concept can also apply to wired networks and to software interaction.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] A mesh network whose nodes are all connected to each other is a fully connected network.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] Fully connected wired networks are more secure and reliable: problems in a cable affect only the two nodes attached to it.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] In such networks, however, the number of cables, and therefore the cost, goes up rapidly as the number of nodes increases.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] Shortest path bridging and TRILL each allow Ethernet switches to be connected in a mesh topology and allow for all paths to be active.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] IP routing supports multiple paths from source to destination.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] A wireless mesh network (WMN) is a network made up of radio nodes organized in a mesh topology.
[src:z-wave-deep/mesh-networking] It can also be a form of wireless ad hoc network.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] These are similar to wireless ad hoc networks in the sense that they rely on wireless connectivity and spontaneous formation of networks so that sensor data can be transported wirelessly.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] WSNs monitor physical conditions, such as temperature, sound, and pressure.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Modern networks are bi-directional, both collecting data and enabling control of sensor activity.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The development of these networks was motivated by military applications such as battlefield surveillance.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Such networks are used in industrial and consumer applications, such as industrial process monitoring and control and machine health monitoring and agriculture.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] A WSN is built of "nodes" – from a few to hundreds or thousands, where each node is connected to other sensors.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Each such node typically has several parts: a radio transceiver with an internal antenna or connection to an external antenna, a microcontroller, an electronic circuit for interfacing with the sensors and an energy source, usually a battery or an embedded form of energy harvesting.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] A sensor node might vary in size from a shoebox to (theoretically) a grain of dust, although microscopic dimensions have yet to be realized.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Sensor node cost is similarly variable, ranging from a few to hundreds of dollars, depending on node sophistication.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Size and cost constraints constrain resources such as energy, memory, computational speed and communications bandwidth.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The topology of a WSN can vary from a simple star network to an advanced multi-hop wireless mesh network.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Propagation can employ routing or flooding.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] As of 2010, wireless sensor networks had deployed approximately 120 million remote units worldwide.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Area monitoring is a common application of WSNs.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] In area monitoring, the WSN is deployed over a region where some phenomenon is to be monitored.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] A military example is the use of sensors to detect enemy intrusion; a civilian example is the geo-fencing of gas or oil pipelines.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] There are several types of sensor networks for medical applications: implanted, wearable, and environment-embedded.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Implantable medical devices are those that are inserted inside the human body.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wearable devices are used on the body surface of a human or just at close proximity of the user.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Environment-embedded systems employ sensors contained in the environment.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Possible applications include body position measurement, location of persons, overall monitoring of ill patients in hospitals and at home.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Devices embedded in the environment track the physical state of a person for continuous health diagnosis, using as input the data from a network of depth cameras, a sensing floor, or other similar devices.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Body-area networks can collect information about an individual's health, fitness, and energy expenditure.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] In health care applications the privacy and authenticity of user data has prime importance.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Especially due to the integration of sensor networks, with IoT, the user authentication becomes more challenging; however, a solution is presented in recent work.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks have been used to monitor various species and habitats, beginning with the Great Duck Island Deployment, including marmots, cane toads in Australia and zebras in Kenya.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] There are many applications in monitoring environmental parameters, examples of which are given below.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] They share the extra challenges of harsh environments and reduced power supply.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Experiments have shown that personal exposure to air pollution in cities can vary a lot.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Therefore, it is of interest to have higher temporal and spatial resolution of pollutants and particulates.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] For research purposes, wireless sensor networks have been deployed to monitor the concentration of dangerous gases for citizens (e.g., in London).
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] However, sensors for gases and particulate matter suffer from high unit-to-unit variability, cross-sensitivities, and (concept) drift.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Moreover, the quality of data is currently insufficient for trustworthy decision-making, as field calibration leads to unreliable measurement results, and frequent recalibration might be required.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] A possible solution could be blind calibration or the usage of mobile references.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] A network of Sensor Nodes can be installed in a forest to detect when a fire has started.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The nodes can be equipped with sensors to measure temperature, humidity and gases which are produced by fire in the trees or vegetation.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The early detection is crucial for a successful action of the firefighters; thanks to Wireless Sensor Networks, the fire brigade will be able to know when a fire is started and how it is spreading.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] A landslide detection system makes use of a wireless sensor network to detect the slight movements of soil and changes in various parameters that may occur before or during a landslide.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Through the data gathered it may be possible to know the impending occurrence of landslides long before it actually happens.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Water quality monitoring involves analyzing water properties in dams, rivers, lakes and oceans, as well as underground water reserves.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The use of many wireless distributed sensors enables the creation of a more accurate map of the water status, and allows the permanent deployment of monitoring stations in locations of difficult access, without the need of manual data retrieval.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks can be effective in preventing adverse consequences of natural disasters, like floods.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless nodes have been deployed successfully in rivers, where changes in water levels must be monitored in real time.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks have been developed for machinery condition-based maintenance (CBM) as they offer significant cost savings and enable new functionality.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensors can be placed in locations difficult or impossible to reach with a wired system, such as rotating machinery and untethered vehicles.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks also are used for the collection of data for monitoring of environmental information.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This can be as simple as monitoring the temperature in a fridge or the level of water in overflow tanks in nuclear power plants.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The statistical information can then be used to show how systems have been working.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The advantage of WSNs over conventional loggers is the "live" data feed that is possible.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Monitoring the quality and level of water includes many activities such as checking the quality of underground or surface water and ensuring a country's water infrastructure for the benefit of both human and animal.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] It may be used to protect the wastage of water.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] WSN can be used to monitor the condition of civil infrastructure and related geo-physical processes close to real time, and over long periods through data logging, using appropriately interfaced sensors.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks are used to monitor wine production, both in the field and the cellar.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The Wide Area Tracking System (WATS) is a prototype network for detecting a ground-based nuclear device such as a nuclear "briefcase bomb".
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] WATS is being developed at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (LLNL).
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] WATS would be made up of wireless gamma and neutron sensors connected through a communications network.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Data picked up by the sensors undergoes "data fusion", which converts the information into easily interpreted forms; this data fusion is the most important aspect of the system.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The data fusion process occurs *within* the sensor network rather than at a centralized computer and is performed by a specially developed algorithm based on Bayesian statistics.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] WATS would not use a centralized computer for analysis because researchers found that factors such as latency and available bandwidth tended to create significant bottlenecks.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Data processed in the field by the network itself (by transferring small amounts of data between neighboring sensors) is faster and makes the network more scalable.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] An important factor in WATS development is *ease of deployment*, since more sensors both improves the detection rate and reduces false alarms.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] WATS sensors could be deployed in permanent positions or mounted in vehicles for mobile protection of specific locations.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] One barrier to the implementation of WATS is the size, weight, energy requirements and cost of currently available wireless sensors.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The development of improved sensors is a major component of current research at the Nonproliferation, Arms Control, and International Security (NAI) Directorate at LLNL.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] House of Representatives' Military Research and Development Subcommittee on October 1, 1997, during a hearing on nuclear terrorism and countermeasures.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] On August 4, 1998, in a subsequent meeting of that subcommittee, Chairman Curt Weldon stated that research funding for WATS had been cut by the Clinton administration to a subsistence level and that the program had been poorly re-organized.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Studies show that using sensors for incident monitoring improve the response of firefighters and police to an unexpected situation.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] For an early detection of incidents we can use acoustic sensors to detect a spike in the noise of the city because of a possible accident, or use termic sensors to detect a possible fire.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Using low-power electronics, WSN:s can be cost-efficiently applied also in supply chains in various industries.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Cross-layer is becoming an important studying area for wireless communications.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The traditional layered approach does not have the ability to adapt to the environmental change.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Because of the interference between the different users, access conflicts, fading, and the change of environment in the wireless sensor networks, traditional layered approach for wired networks is not applicable to wireless networks.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] So the cross-layer can be used to make the optimal modulation to improve the transmission performance, such as data rate, energy efficiency, quality of service (QoS), etc.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Sensor nodes can be imagined as small computers which are extremely basic in terms of their interfaces and their components.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] They usually consist of a *processing unit* with limited computational power and limited memory, *sensors* or MEMS (including specific conditioning circuitry), a *communication device* (usually radio transceivers or alternatively optical), and a power source usually in the form of a battery.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Other possible inclusions are energy harvesting modules, secondary ASICs, and possibly secondary communication interface (e.g.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The base stations are one or more components of the WSN with much more computational, energy and communication resources.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] They act as a gateway between sensor nodes and the end user as they typically forward data from the WSN on to a server.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Other special components in routing based networks are routers, designed to compute, calculate and distribute the routing tables.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] One major challenge in a WSN is to produce *low cost* and *tiny* sensor nodes.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] There are an increasing number of small companies producing WSN hardware and the commercial situation can be compared to home computing in the 1970s.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Many of the nodes are still in the research and development stage, particularly their software.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Also inherent to sensor network adoption is the use of very low power methods for radio communication and data acquisition.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] In many applications, a WSN communicates with a local area network or wide area network through a gateway.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The Gateway acts as a bridge between the WSN and the other network.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This enables data to be stored and processed by devices with more resources, for example, in a remotely located server.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] A wireless wide area network used primarily for low-power devices is known as a Low-Power Wide-Area Network (LPWAN).
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] There are several wireless standards and solutions for sensor node connectivity.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Thread and Zigbee can connect sensors operating at 2.4 GHz with a data rate of 250 kbit/s.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Many use a lower frequency to increase radio range (typically 1 km), for example Z-wave operates at 915 MHz (in North America) and in the EU 868 MHz has been widely used but these have a lower data rate (typically 50 kbit/s).
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The IEEE 802.15.4 working group provides a standard for low power device connectivity and commonly sensors and smart meters use one of these standards for connectivity.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] With the emergence of Internet of Things, many other proposals have been made to provide sensor connectivity.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] LoRa is a form of LPWAN which provides long range low power wireless connectivity for devices, which has been used in smart meters and other long range sensor applications.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] NarrowBand IOT and LTE-M can connect up to millions of sensors and devices using cellular technology.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Energy is the scarcest resource of WSN nodes, and it determines the lifetime of WSNs.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] WSNs may be deployed in large numbers in various environments, including remote and hostile regions, where ad hoc communications are a key component.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Lifetime maximization: Energy/Power Consumption of the sensing device should be minimized and sensor nodes should be energy efficient since their limited energy resource determines their lifetime.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] To conserve power, wireless sensor nodes normally power off both the radio transmitter and the radio receiver when not in use.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks are composed of low-energy, small-size, and low-range unattended sensor nodes.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Recently, it has been observed that by periodically turning on and off the sensing and communication capabilities of sensor nodes, we can significantly reduce the active time and thus prolong network lifetime.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] However, this duty cycling may result in high network latency, routing overhead, and neighbor discovery delays due to asynchronous sleep and wake-up scheduling.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] These limitations call for a countermeasure for duty-cycled wireless sensor networks which should minimize routing information, routing traffic load, and energy consumption.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Researchers from Sungkyunkwan University have proposed a lightweight non-increasing delivery-latency interval routing referred as LNDIR.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This scheme can discover minimum latency routes at each non-increasing delivery-latency interval instead of each time slot.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Simulation experiments demonstrated the validity of this novel approach in minimizing routing information stored at each sensor.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Furthermore, this novel routing can also guarantee the minimum delivery latency from each source to the sink.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Performance improvements of up to 12-fold and 11-fold are observed in terms of routing traffic load reduction and energy efficiency, respectively, as compared to existing schemes.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Operating systems for wireless sensor network nodes are typically less complex than general-purpose operating systems.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] They more strongly resemble embedded systems, for two reasons.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] First, wireless sensor networks are typically deployed with a particular application in mind, rather than as a general platform.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Second, a need for low costs and low power leads most wireless sensor nodes to have low-power microcontrollers ensuring that mechanisms such as virtual memory are either unnecessary or too expensive to implement.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] It is therefore possible to use embedded operating systems such as eCos or uC/OS for sensor networks.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] However, such operating systems are often designed with real-time properties.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS, developed by David Culler, is perhaps the first operating system specifically designed for wireless sensor networks.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS is based on an event-driven programming model instead of multithreading.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS programs are composed of *event handlers* and *tasks* with run-to-completion semantics.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] When an external event occurs, such as an incoming data packet or a sensor reading, TinyOS signals the appropriate event handler to handle the event.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Event handlers can post tasks that are scheduled by the TinyOS kernel some time later.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] LiteOS is a newly developed OS for wireless sensor networks, which provides UNIX-like abstraction and support for the C programming language.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Contiki, developed by Adam Dunkels, is an OS which uses a simpler programming style in C while providing advances such as 6LoWPAN and Protothreads.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] RIOT (operating system) is a more recent real-time OS including similar functionality to Contiki.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] PreonVM is an OS for wireless sensor networks, which provides 6LoWPAN based on Contiki and support for the Java programming language.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Examples include Xively and the Wikisensing platform Archived 2021-06-09 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Such platforms simplify online collaboration between users over diverse data sets ranging from energy and environment data to that collected from transport services.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Other services include allowing developers to embed real-time graphs & widgets in websites; analyse and process historical data pulled from the data feeds; send real-time alerts from any datastream to control scripts, devices and environments.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] At present, agent-based modeling and simulation is the only paradigm which allows the simulation of complex behavior in the environments of wireless sensors (such as flocking).
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Agent-based simulation of wireless sensor and ad hoc networks is a relatively new paradigm.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Agent-based modelling was originally based on social simulation.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Network simulators like Opnet, Tetcos NetSim and NS can be used to simulate a wireless sensor network.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Network localization refers to the problem of estimating the location of wireless sensor nodes during deployments and in dynamic settings.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] For ultra-low power sensors, size, cost and environment precludes the use of Global Positioning System receivers on sensors.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] In 2000, Nirupama Bulusu, John Heidemann and Deborah Estrin first motivated and proposed a radio connectivity based system for localization of wireless sensor networks.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Subsequently, such localization systems have been referred to as range free localization systems, and many localization systems for wireless sensor networks have been subsequently proposed including AHLoS, APS, and Stardust.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Sensors and devices used in wireless sensor networks are state-of-the-art technology with the lowest possible price.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The sensor measurements we get from these devices are therefore often noisy, incomplete and inaccurate.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Researchers studying wireless sensor networks hypothesize that much more information can be extracted from hundreds of unreliable measurements spread across a field of interest than from a smaller number of high-quality, high-reliability instruments with the same total cost.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Macro-programming is a term coined by Matt Welsh.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] It refers to programming the entire sensor network as an ensemble, rather than individual sensor nodes.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Another way to macro-program a network is to view the sensor network as a database, which was popularized by the TinyDB system developed by Sam Madden.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Reprogramming is the process of updating the code on the sensor nodes.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The most feasible form of reprogramming is remote reprogramming whereby the code is disseminated wirelessly while the nodes are deployed.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Different reprogramming protocols exist that provide different levels of speed of operation, reliability, energy expenditure, requirement of code resident on the nodes, suitability to different wireless environments, resistance to DoS, etc.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Infrastructure-less architecture (i.e. no gateways are included, etc.) and inherent requirements (i.e. unattended working environment, etc.) of WSNs might pose several weak points that attract adversaries.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Therefore, security is a big concern when WSNs are deployed for special applications such as military and healthcare.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Owing to their unique characteristics, traditional security methods of computer networks would be useless (or less effective) for WSNs.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Hence, lack of security mechanisms would cause intrusions towards those networks.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] These intrusions need to be detected and mitigation methods should be applied.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] There have been important innovations in securing wireless sensor networks.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Most wireless embedded networks use omni-directional antennas and therefore neighbors can overhear communication in and out of nodes.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This was used this to develop a primitive called "*local monitoring*" which was used for detection of sophisticated attacks, like blackhole or wormhole, which degrade the throughput of large networks to close-to-zero.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This primitive has since been used by many researchers and commercial wireless packet sniffers.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This was subsequently refined for more sophisticated attacks such as with collusion, mobility, and multi-antenna, multi-channel devices.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] If a centralized architecture is used in a sensor network and the central node fails, then the entire network will collapse, however the reliability of the sensor network can be increased by using a distributed control architecture.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] To provide nodes with backup in case of failure of the central node.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] There is also no centralised body to allocate the resources and they have to be self organized.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] The data gathered from wireless sensor networks is usually saved in the form of numerical data in a central base station.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] To reduce communication costs some algorithms remove or reduce nodes' redundant sensor information and avoid forwarding data that is of no use.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This technique has been used, for instance, for distributed anomaly detection or distributed optimization.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] As nodes can inspect the data they forward, they can measure averages or directionality for example of readings from other nodes.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] For example, in sensing and monitoring applications, it is generally the case that neighboring sensor nodes monitoring an environmental feature typically register similar values.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This kind of data redundancy due to the spatial correlation between sensor observations inspires techniques for in-network data aggregation and mining.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Aggregation reduces the amount of network traffic which helps to reduce energy consumption on sensor nodes.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This is a form of in-network processing where sensor nodes are assumed to be unsecured with limited available energy, while the base station is assumed to be secure with unlimited available energy.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Aggregation complicates the already existing security challenges for wireless sensor networks and requires new security techniques tailored specifically for these scenarios.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Providing security to aggregate data in wireless sensor networks is known as *secure data aggregation in WSN*. were the first few works discussing techniques for secure data aggregation in wireless sensor networks.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Two main security challenges in secure data aggregation are confidentiality and integrity of data.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] While encryption is traditionally used to provide end to end confidentiality in wireless sensor network, the aggregators in a secure data aggregation scenario need to decrypt the encrypted data to perform aggregation.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] This exposes the plaintext at the aggregators, making the data vulnerable to attacks from an adversary.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Similarly an aggregator can inject false data into the aggregate and make the base station accept false data.
[src:z-wave-deep/wireless-sensor-network] Thus, while data aggregation improves energy efficiency of a network, it complicates the existing security challenges.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave provides the application layer interoperability between home control systems of different manufacturers that are a part of its alliance.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The Z-Wave protocol was developed by Zensys, a Danish company based in Copenhagen, in 1999.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] That year, Zensys introduced a consumer light-control system, which evolved into Z-Wave as a proprietary system on a chip (SoC) home automation protocol on an unlicensed frequency band in the 900 MHz range.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Its 100 series chip set was released in 2003, and its 200 series was released in May 2005, with the ZW0201 chip offering high performance at a low cost.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Its 500 series chip, also known as Z-Wave Plus, was released in March 2013, with four times the memory, improved wireless range, improved battery life, an enhanced S2 security framework, and the SmartStart setup feature.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Its 700 series chip was released in 2019, with the ability to communicate up to 100 meters directly from point-to-point, or 800 meters across an entire Z-Wave network, an extended battery life of up to 10 years, and comes with S2 and SmartStart technology.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In July 2019, the Z-Wave Plus v2 certification was announced.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] It is designed for devices built on the 700 platform.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The Z-Wave Long Range (LR) specification was announced in September 2020, a new specification with up to four-times the wireless range of standard Z-Wave.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave's 800 series chip was released in late 2021, with improved security and battery life over the 700 series.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The technology began to catch on in North America around 2005, when five companies, including Danfoss, Ingersoll-Rand and Leviton Manufacturing, adopted Z-Wave.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] They formed the Z-Wave Alliance, whose objective is to promote the use of Z-Wave technology, with all certified products by companies in the Alliance interoperable.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In 2005, Bessemer Venture Partners led a $16 million third seed round for Zensys.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In May 2006, Intel Capital announced that it was investing in Zensys, a few days after Intel joined the Z-Wave Alliance.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In 2008, Zensys received investments from Panasonic, Cisco Systems, Palamon Capital Partners and Sunstone Capital.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave was acquired by Sigma Designs in December 2008.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Following the acquisition, Z-Wave's U.S. headquarters in Fremont, California were merged with Sigma's headquarters in Milpitas, California.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] As part of the changes, the trademark interests in Z-Wave were retained in the United States by Sigma Designs and acquired by a subsidiary of Aeotec Group in Europe.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] On January 23, 2018, Sigma announced it planned to sell the Z-Wave technology and business assets to Silicon Labs for $240 million, and the sale was completed on April 18, 2018.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In 2019, Z-Wave was spun off into an independent organization, and by 2025 it was a completely open standard.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] On February 4, 2026, Texas Instruments announced that it would be acquiring Silicon Labs for approximately $7.5 billion, with the transaction expected to close in early 2027.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In 2005, there were six products on the market that used Z-Wave technology.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] By 2012, as smart home technology was becoming increasingly popular, there were approximately 600 products using Z-Wave technology available in the U.S.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] As of February 2026, there are over 4,500 Z-Wave certified interoperable products, with more than 100 million devices installed across the globe.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The Z-Wave product market size was estimated at $14.32 billion USD in 2025, and is expected to reach $22.13 billion USD by 2032.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave's interoperability at the application layer ensures that devices can share information and allows all Z-Wave hardware and software to work together.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Its wireless mesh networking technology enables any node to talk to adjacent nodes directly or indirectly, controlling any additional nodes.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Nodes that are within range communicate directly with one another.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] If they aren't within range, they can link with another node that is within range of both to access and exchange information.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In September 2016, certain parts of the Z-Wave technology were made publicly available, when then-owner Sigma Designs released a public version of Z-Wave's interoperability layer, with the software added to Z-Wave's open-source library.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The Z-Wave MAC/PHY is globally standardized by the International Telecommunication Union as ITU 9959 radio.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The open-source availability allows software developers to integrate Z-Wave into devices with fewer restrictions.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave's S2 security, Z/IP for transporting Z-Wave signals over IP networks, and Z-Wave middleware are all open source as of 2016.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In 2020, the Z-Wave Alliance ratified the Z-Wave specification, adding the application to open-source development.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The Alliance Technical Working Group manages Z-Wave specification development and maintains a library of standard implementations for Z-Wave compliant products.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Established in 2005 and re-incorporated as a non-profit in 2020, the Z-Wave Alliance is a member-driven standards development organization dedicated to market development, technical Z-Wave specification and device certification, and education on Z-Wave technology.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave Alliance is a consortium of over 300 companies in the residential and commercial connected technology market.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave Alliance certifies devices to standards that guarantee interoperability with full backwards compatibility among all generations of Z-Wave devices.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] These standards include specifications for reliability, range, power consumption, and device interoperability.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In February 2014, the first product was certified by Z-Wave Plus.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In 2016, the Alliance launched a Z-Wave Certified Installer Training program to give installers, integrators and dealers the tools to deploy Z-Wave networks and devices in their residential and commercial jobs.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] That year, the Alliance announced the Z-Wave Certified Installer Toolkit (Z-CIT), a diagnostics and troubleshooting device that can be used during network and device setup and can also function as a remote diagnostics tool.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave Long Range (ZWLR) was announced in September 2020, a new specification with an increased range over regular Z-Wave signals.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The ZWLR specification is managed and certified under the Z-Wave Plus v2 certification.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Under ideal conditions, ZWLR allows devices to communicate directly with a hub at a distance of up to 1.5 miles, and supports up to 4,000 devices on a single network.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] On March 15, 2022, the Z-Wave Alliance announced that Ecolink, a security and home automation brand, was the first to complete Z-Wave LR certification, with the Ecolink 700 Series Garage Door Controller.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] By January 2026, there were 125 certified Z-Wave Long Range devices on the market.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave Alliance maintains the Z-Wave certification program.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] There are two components to Z-Wave certification: technical certification and market certification.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In December 2019, Z-Wave announced the Z-Wave Source Code Project, in which it would release the source code to its platform, for members to contribute to the advancement of the standard, under the supervision of the newly-established OS Work Group.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The project is available to alliance members on GitHub.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In 2022, the completion of the Z-Wave Source Code Project was announced.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] It allows members to develop Z-Wave devices on a variety of third-party silicon chips, contribute code under the supervision of the Open Source Work Group, and implement interoperability between Z-Wave and other protocols.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In December 2019, the Z-Wave Alliance announced that the Z-Wave specification would become a ratified, multi-source wireless standard.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] It includes the ITU.G9959 PHY/MAC radio specification, the application layer, the network layer, and the host-device communication protocol.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Instead of being a single-source specification, it will become a multi-source, wireless smart home standard developed by collective working group members of the Z-Wave Alliance.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The Z-Wave Alliance would become a standards development organization (SDO), while continuing to manage the certification program.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In August 2020, the Z-Wave Alliance officially became incorporated as an independent nonprofit standards development organization, with seven founding members under its new SDO structure: Alarm.com, Assa Abloy, Leedarson, Ring, Silicon Labs, StratIS, and Qolsys.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Under the SDO, there are new membership levels, workgroups, and committees, including technical working groups specific to features, and certification, security, and marketing groups.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In 2025, Z-Wave released the 2024B specification for improved functionality and regulatory compliance, following the release of 2024A the previous year.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] They also introduced the new Accelerator membership level, for startups and young IoT companies.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave is designed to provide reliable, low-latency transmission of small data packets at data rates up to 100 kbit/s, and is suitable for control and sensor applications, unlike Wi-Fi and other IEEE 802.11-based wireless LAN systems that are designed primarily for high data rates.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Communication distance between two nodes is 200 meters line of sight outdoors and 50 meters line of sight indoors, and with message ability to hop up to four times between nodes, it gives enough coverage for most residential houses.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Modulation is frequency-shift keying (FSK) with Manchester encoding, and other supported modulations schemes include GFSK and DSSS-OQPSK.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave uses the Part 15 unlicensed industrial, scientific, and medical (ISM) band, operating on varying frequencies globally.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] For instance, in Europe it operates at the 868-869 MHz band while in North America the band varies from 908-916 MHz when Z-Wave is operating as a mesh network and 912-920 MHz when Z-Wave is operating with a star topology in Z-Wave LR mode.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave's mesh network band competes with some cordless telephones and other consumer electronics devices, but avoids interference with Wi-Fi, Bluetooth and other systems that operate on the crowded 2.4 GHz band.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The lower layers, MAC and PHY, are described by ITU-T G.9959 and fully backwards compatible.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In 2012, the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) included the Z-Wave PHY and MAC layers as an option in its G.9959 standard for wireless devices under 1 GHz.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Data rates include 9600 bit/s and 40 kbit/s, with output power at 1 mW or 0 dBm.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Traditional hub-and-spoke networks include one central hub or access point to which all devices are connected, such as a wireless device connecting to a router.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave devices create a mesh network, where devices can communicate with each other in addition to the central hub.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Advantages to a mesh network include greater range and compatibility, and a stronger network.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave LR devices operate on a star network topology that features the hub at a central point and then establishes a direct connection to each device, rather than sending signals from node to node until the intended destination is met, as in a mesh network.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The key difference between a star network and a mesh network is the direct hub-to-device connection.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Both Z-Wave LR and traditional Z-Wave nodes can coexist within the same network.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The simplest network is a single controllable device and a primary controller.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Devices can communicate to one another by using intermediate nodes to actively route around and circumvent household obstacles or radio dead spots that might occur in the multipath environment of a house.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] A message from node A to node C can be successfully delivered even if the two nodes are not within range, providing that a third node B can communicate with nodes A and C.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] If the preferred route is unavailable, the message originator will attempt other routes until a path is found to the C node.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Therefore, a Z-Wave network can span much farther than the radio range of a single unit; however, with several of these hops a slight delay may be introduced between the control command and the desired result.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Additional devices can be added at any time, as can secondary controllers, including traditional hand-held controllers, key-fob controllers, wall-switch controllers and PC applications designed for management and control of a Z-Wave network.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] A Z-Wave network can consist of up to 232 devices, or up to 4,000 nodes on a single smart-home network with Z-Wave LR.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Both allow the option of bridging networks if more devices are required.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] A device must be "included" to the Z-Wave network before it can be controlled via Z-Wave.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] This process (also known as "pairing" and "adding") is usually achieved by pressing a sequence of buttons on the controller and on the device being added to the network.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] This sequence only needs to be performed once, after which the device is always recognized by the controller.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Devices can be removed from the Z-Wave network by a similar process.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The controller learns the signal strength between the devices during the inclusion process and will utilize this information when calculating routes.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In the event that devices have been moved and the previously stored signal strength is wrong, the controller may issue a new route resolution through one or more explore frames.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Each Z-Wave network is identified by a Network ID, and each device is further identified by a Node ID.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The Network ID (also called Home ID) is the common identification of all nodes belonging to one logical Z-Wave network.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The Network ID has a length of 4 bytes (32 bits) and is assigned to each device, by the primary controller, when the device is "included" into the Network.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Nodes with different Network IDs cannot communicate with each other.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The Node ID is the address of a single node in the network.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The Node ID has a length of 1 byte (8 bits) and must be unique in its network.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The Z-Wave chip is optimized for battery-powered devices, and most of the time remains in a power saving mode to consume less energy, waking up only to perform its function.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] With Z-Wave mesh networks, each device in the house bounces wireless signals around the house, which results in low power consumption, allowing devices to work for years without needing to replace batteries.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] For Z-Wave units to be able to route unsolicited messages, they cannot be in sleep mode.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Therefore, battery-operated devices are not designed as repeater units.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Mobile devices, such as remote controls, are also excluded since Z-Wave assumes that all repeater capable devices in the network remain in their original detected position.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave is based on a proprietary design, supported by Sigma Designs as its primary chip vendor, but the Z-Wave business unit was acquired by Silicon Labs in 2018.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In December 2019, Silicon Labs announced that it would release the Z-Wave specification as an open wireless standard for development to be certified by the Z-Wave Alliance.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The vulnerability was not due to a flaw in the Z-Wave protocol specification but was an implementation error by the door-lock manufacturer.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] On November 17, 2016, the Z-Wave Alliance announced stronger security standards for devices receiving Z-Wave Certification as of April 2, 2017.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Known as Security 2 (or S2), it provides advanced security for smart home devices, gateways and hubs.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] It shores up encryption standards for transmissions between nodes, and mandates new pairing procedures for each device, with unique PIN or QR codes on each device.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The new layer of authentication is intended to prevent hackers from taking control of unsecured or poorly-secured devices.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] According to the Z-Wave Alliance, the new security standard is the most advanced security available on the market for smart home devices and controllers, gateways and hubs.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The 800 series chip, released in late 2021, continues to support standard S2 security capabilities, as well as Silicon Labs Secure Vault technology, enabling wireless devices with PSA Certification Level 3 security.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In 2022, researchers published several vulnerabilities in the Z-Wave chipsets up to the 700 series, based on an open-source protocol-specific fuzzer.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] As a result, depending on the chipset and device, an attacker within Z-Wave radio range can deny service, cause devices to crash, deplete batteries, intercept, observe, and replay traffic, and control vulnerable devices.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave devices with 100, 200, 300 series chipsets cannot be updated to fix the vulnerabilities.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] For devices with 500 and 700 chipset series those vulnerabilities could be mitigated through firmware updates.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The chip for Z-Wave nodes is the ZW0500, built around an Intel MCS-51 microcontroller with an internal system clock of 32 MHz.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The RF part of the chip contains an GisFSK transceiver for a software selectable frequency.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] With a power supply of 2.2-3.6 volts, it consumes 23mA in transmit mode.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Its features include AES-128 encryption, a 100 kbit/s wireless channel, concurrent listening on multiple channels, and USB VCP support.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] At the Consumer Electronics Show on January 8, 2018, Sigma Designs introduced its Z-Wave 700 platform.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The 700 series chip was released in 2019.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] It enables a new class of smart home devices that can be used outdoors, with a range of up to 300 feet, and that can operate on a coin-cell battery for up to a decade.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Though the 700 series uses a 32-bit ARM Cortex SoC, it remains backward compatible with all other Z-Wave devices.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] It includes enhanced S2 security framework as well as the SmartStart setup feature.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In July 2019, the Z-Wave Alliance announced Z-Wave Plus v2 certification, designed for devices built on the 700 platform, for stronger interoperability and security, and an easier installation process.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave Long Range (ZWLR) was announced in September 2020, a new specification with an improved range over regular Z-Wave signals.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The specification supports a maximum output power of 30 dBm, which can be used to bolster transmission range by up to several miles.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In testing, ZWLR had a transmission distance of 1-mile (1.6 km) direct line of sight utilizing +14-dBm output power.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave LR is an extra 100-kb/s DSSS OQPSK modulation addition to the Z-Wave protocol.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] The modulation is treated as a fourth channel, allowing gateways to add long range nodes to the existing Z-Wave channel scanning.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave LR also increases scalability on a single smart-home network by up to 4,000 nodes, a 20x increase compared to Z-Wave.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] ZWLR operates on low power so that sensors can last for 10 years on a single coin cell.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] It is backwards compatible and interoperable with other Z-Wave devices.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In December 2021, Silicon Labs announced the availability of the Z-Wave 800 system-on-chips and modules for the Z-Wave smart home and automation ecosystem.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] It is described as secure, ultra-low powered, and wireless, for Internet of Things devices, with an improved battery life as compared to the 700 series.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] In August 2023, Z-Wave announced that Trident IoT would be a new direct supplier of silicon chips and modules for Z-Wave devices, offer alliance members product design and development services, and work as a certification lab for Z-Wave devices.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Trident IoT and Semtech partnered to create a multi-protocol IoT development platform, combining Semtech's LoRa Plus transceivers with Trident's ELCap platform, integrating LoRa with Z-Wave connectivity to simplify IoT product development.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] For smart home wireless networking, there are numerous technologies working together.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave operates on the sub-1 GHz (low bandwidth) vs 2.4 GHz (high bandwidth) to capitalize on the application-level benefits of low power, long range, less RF interference.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] WiFi and Bluetooth operate on the 2.4 GHz bandwidth which manages a lot of traffic among devices that consume a lot of power.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Other network standards include Bluetooth LE and Thread.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave has better interoperability than ZigBee, but ZigBee has a faster data transmission rate.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Thread and Zigbee operate on the busy Wi-Fi standard frequency of 2.4 GHz, while Z-Wave operates below 1 GHz, which has reduced noise and congestion, and a greater coverage area.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] OpenZWave is a library, written in C++ and wrappers and supporting projects, to interface different languages and protocol(s) allowing anyone to create applications to control devices on a Z-Wave network, without requiring in-depth knowledge of the Z-Wave protocol.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] This software is currently aimed at application developers who wish to incorporate Z-Wave functionality into their applications.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] As of November 17, 2022 OpenZWave is no longer being actively maintained.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Matter, brought forth by the Connectivity Standards Alliance, and founded on December 19, 2019, aims to unify device communication so that connected devices will work together, across both wireless technologies and smart home ecosystems.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] Z-Wave networks have IP at the gateway level, enabling cloud connectivity to Matter.
[src:z-wave-deep/z-wave] They can also work together at the local network level.
